\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$\frac{{dm}}{{dt}} \approx \alpha$\end{document} and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$m \approx \alpha \cdot t$\end{document}. Thus, the slope in the linear increase of the mRNA level after induction in Figure 3A (dashed lines) is equal to the transcription rate, α. Analysing the slopes, we obtained 5.0 (±0.3)/min and 4.9 (±0.2)/min for the transcription rate of the head and tail of the mRNA, respectively.

Alternatively, we can deduce the degradation rate using the steady state level of mRNAs together with the transcription rate, α, obtained above; at the steady state, the Equation (1) yields \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
